<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-556-443  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 556 443.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 29 1990 v7 n43 p10(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Wang information-retrieval system to ease full-text searches.andO;(Wang Laboratories Inc.) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Higgins, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Wang Laboratories Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    WANC.andO;Product:   Wang Professional Research System (Document processing system)(Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionDocument Management SystemsSearchingInformation Storage and Retrieval.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steve HigginsandM;A Wang Laboratories Inc. division will charge into the information-retrievalarena early next year with a program that will work with the company'sexisting document-management software to remove some of the complexityassociated with full-text searches.andM;As with other text-retrieval programs, the forthcoming Wang ProfessionalResearch System (PRS) will lead users to paragraphs, passages or wholedocuments that contain specific words or phrases, according to BarbaraDeYoung, a senior product manager for Wang Informatics Legal and ProfessionalSystems Inc. in Phoenix.andM;PRS, however, can be used in conjunction with the division's ProFounddocument-management software to let users sidestep one of the standardpitfalls of text-retrieval systems -- the need to translate word-processingdocuments into a format readable by the text-retrieval system, said DeYoung.andM;PRS, which runs on DOS PCs across NetBIOS-compatible networks, will work withProFound to automatically store documents in the text-retrieval database ondemand.andM;Each time a document is created in ProFound, the user is asked to complete ashort profile, which can include a request to archive the document in PRS.andO;When that new document is stored, PRS automatically archives it.andP;  If thedocument is altered, an updated copy is written to PRS, DeYoung said.andM;PRS also includes a &quot;notebook&quot; feature that lets users create a compositedocument containing key passages from numerous documents.andP;  When the chosentext is retrieved, users highlight the desired passage and store it in thenotebook.andM;Pricing for PRS, which Wang will ship to beta sites next month, will be$3,495 for a five-user version and $250 for each additional user.andP;  ProFoundcosts $995 for five users.andM;PRS will be available through Wang's Informatics Legal and ProfessionalSystems division -- which previously developed software solely for legal andother niche markets -- and its resellers.andO;</TEXT></DOC>